  "prompt": "What are some examples of fiction written in the future tense?",
  "response": "Writing fiction entirely in the future tense is quite rare, as it can be grammatically awkward and challenging to maintain. However, there are some experimental works and short pieces that use future tense to create a unique narrative style. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. Short stories or experimental pieces where the entire narrative is written in future tense, often to create a sense of anticipation or uncertainty.\n\n2. Some speculative fiction or science fiction works might use future tense to describe potential scenarios or hypothetical futures.\n\n3. Rare literary experiments where authors play with narrative perspective and tense.\n\nWhile not a comprehensive list of published works, these are the most common contexts where future tense fiction might appear. Most fiction is written in past or present tense, with future tense typically used sparingly for specific narrative effects.\n\nIf you're looking for specific published examples, they would likely be found in avant-garde literary journals or experimental writing collections.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these points or discuss the challenges of writing in future tense?",
